ling itself as a complex right they should be afforded in cities that violently structure their movements and energies. What emerges in Feels Right is a sensorial portrait of the critical, black queer geographies and collectivities that emerge in social dance settings and in the broader neoliberal city.Duke University Press Scholars of Color First Book Award recipient  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aCommunication and sexzIllinoiszChicago. 0aNightlifezIllinoiszChicago. 0aQueer theoryzIllinoiszChicago. 0aSexual minoritieszIllinoiszChicagoxSocial conditions. 0aSexual minority culturezIllinoiszChicago. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh  aqueer nightlife studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076691240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478023319?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478023319423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478023319/original  a978-3-11-076691-2  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles